    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nI was looking into fixing up cupy mutexes and touching some of the locking logic there.  The solution was to use C++ mutexes, which is completely fine, but it lead me down a bit of a rabbit hole, since you need:\n```cython\nif lock.try_lock():\n    with nogil:\n        lock.lock()\ntry:\n    # actual code\nfinally:\n    lock.unlock()\n```\n\nWhich has two things that mildly annoying:\n1. It's easy to forget the `with nogil:` stepping stone.  Which is OK, in the sense that I could wrap those three lines into a single helper, but it's still a common mistake to make if the best solution is to use C++ mutexes.\n2. The try/finally just isn't pretty, especially for the use case where you need to lock down a whole function.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nNow in an ideal world, we could have some syntax like:\n```cython\nwith lock():\n    ...\n```\nand\n```\n@lock()\ndef func():\n    pass\n```\n\nI had discussed with @ngoldbaum about whether there are canonical solution for this to plan for free-threading and I don't think we knew anything better than C++ mutexes.\nUnfortunately, I think enabling that nicer syntax has to be a language feature to make it performant.\n\nTo note: I am coming from existing rlocks/C++ `recurisve_mutex` but I am happy if the precise use-case ends up not being solved!\n\n@ngoldbaum may have a clearer picture of what might be most helpful.  I could for example imagine that we can solve a lot of \"future problems\" with a language feature for critical sections (and for a decorator that might even just nice for `self`).\n(Although, it might still be good to make a small library with locking that is less error prone than C++ mutexes, even if it is just mildly wrapped up C++ mutexes.)\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\nHoping to make things a bit cleaner lead me into the rabbit hole of writing some C++ code (inlined into the `.pyd`) to support something akin a C++ `scoped_lock`, which then allows:\n```cython\ndef function():\n    # lock for the whole function\n    cdef scoped_lock _lock = scoped_lock(self._mutex)\n```\nand also this, but you really want the try/finally if it is more than one statement:\n```\nlock(self._mutex)\n# one statement\nlock.unlock()\n```\n(That version, additionally allows `scoped_lock(mutex, DISABLE_GC)` because cupy has that and maybe even needs it -- I don't know the history yet.)",
