            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "A few quick comments:\n\nWe've got `cython.pymutex` which can be used in a `with` statement, automatically handles the GIL. On older versions of Python we provide a workable fallback based on `PyThread_lock_type` that has the same properties but probably a little slower. \n\nObviously that doesn't have all the flexible combinations that the C++ mutex types have though.\n\nIn the upcoming Cython 3.2 I've created `py_safe` functions for a lot of locking stuff. There's a few examples in https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/3ada45d1852699921f5a28da769a550aa15ae267/tests/run/cpp_mutex.pyx#L48 (search for `py_safe_`). These auto-handle the GIL so again may help with some of what you're after. \n\nI definitely see the appeal of a nice context manager type interface though. \n\n> `scoped_lock(mutex, DISABLE_GC)`\n\nI came to the conclusion that disabling the GC is an unsolvable multi-threading disaster. Essentially because anyone can re-enable it from any other thread. And you can never safely re-enable it because another thread might have also disabled it and be relying on that.\n\n------------\n\nWill look in more detail later and give a more thought through answer.",
