            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Agreed, I have been becoming a bit happier with the situation overall, in part because it isn't actually _that_ bad (the `try/finally` and that locking code) and in part because staring at the code for longer/tidying it up a bit helped.\n\nNot sure I like the `py_safe_*` naming scheme, but I can always `cimport py_safe_* as ...` and the name does make it clearer that the other versions are _not_ safe. They do indeed fill the gap I had been itching to fill concretely.\n\n(Small question/comment, it used to be that unlocking/locking the GIL isn't super fast, although I know Cython has its fast-path. Is it faster now and my `if not lock.try_lock()` should be pretty unnecessary -- beyond being only relevant in light-weight paths?)\n\nMy biggest problem is that my brain for now has a bit of a \"pattern\"/\"best practices\" gap. It feels like there should be clearer pattern for contracts (maybe just naming schemes), even passing `def method(..., scoped_lock &lock)` to proof and document that the method needs locking.\n\n---\n\nAnyway, closing this. There may be a gap somewhere but it is not concrete enough for an issue. The biggest one may well be just Python docs for basic types and maybe some best-practices/patterns.",
