            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> (Small question/comment, it used to be that unlocking/locking the GIL isn't super fast, although I know Cython has its fast-path. Is it faster now and my `if not lock.try_lock()` should be pretty unnecessary -- beyond being only relevant in light-weight paths?)\n\nLast time I measured it - the uncontended reacquire seemed really fast (i.e. if you released the GIL, nothing else wanted it, and then you ask for it back). And of course in freethreading (almost) all acquires are similarly fast. I don't have concrete numbers OTOH though.\n\n> even passing `def method(..., scoped_lock &lock)` to proof and document that the method needs locking.\n\nI definitely do that when writing C++ code for documentation. For Cython it's a little more awkward because you could only only pass `scoped_lock&` to a `cdef` function and not a `def` function.",
